(5542, 432, 'bio', 'Cecilia was called to the Bar in Ontario in 2006 and Alberta in 2011. Cecilia summered and articled at a national firm before joining its Toronto office and later, its Calgary office. Cecilia has a broad range of experience in litigation which includes insurance defence, professional liability and commercial disputes. Since moving to Calgary in April 2011, Cecilia has gained experience in and knowledge of the Oil &amp; Gas industry, particularly with respect to transportation.\r\n\r\nCecilia is an experienced litigator/advocate who works tirelessly for her clients. She has prepared and argued a number of Court applications relating to procedural and substantive issues, conducted JDRs, mediations and numerous examinations. Her advocacy experience also includes acting as second chair with senior partners in complex trials and arbitrations. Cecilia has also appeared before the Court of Appeal (Ontario). Additionally, Cecilia has appeared before regulatory boards and administrative tribunals in Ontario and Alberta on various matters.'),
(5543, 432, '_bio', 'field_5323822abc024'),
(5544, 432, 'representative_work', '<ul>\r\n	<li>Fernandez v. Lau: Successfully defended against the plaintiff ''s motion to amend the Statement of Claim where the limitation period had passed. Successfully demonstrated that the principle of discoverability did not apply and the failure to plead the cause of action in the first instance was a result of solicitor''s inadvertence. The successful defence against this application ultimately resulted in a consent dismissal of the Action.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>R. Charles Allen et al. v. Aspen Group et al.: Represented directors of Aspen Group in a Certification Hearing relating to a Class Action in which the shareholder Plaintiffs alleged that a prospectus filed in relation to a take-over bid contained misrepresentations.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Richard John Charles Galustian and ISI International vs. Skylink Group of Companies Inc.: Assisted U.S. and Dubai Counsel in this shareholders'' dispute relating to logistics companies located in and carrying on business in Iraq, Iran and the U.S. including preparation for a successful forum non conveniens motion.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Metropolitan Toronto Police Widows and Orphan Fund et al. v T elus Communications Inc.: (Class Action under Ontario Representative Plaintiff Rules): Second chair at trial and at the Ontario Court of Appeal representing the class of Plaintiffs relating to damages arising from the wrongful redemption of Bonds issued by Telus''s predecessor B.C. Tel. Successful in securing a $30 Million damages award that was upheld on appeal by the Ontario Court of Appeal.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Paxton v. Ramji: Part of the three person trial and appeal team that successfully defended a physician against allegations of clinical negligence related to his prescription of the teratogenic drug Accutane where the patient subsequently became pregnant and gave birth to a severely compromised child. This was a watershed case in Canada relating to the conflict of duty of physicians when treating women who are, or who may, become pregnant.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Bafaro et al. v. Dowd et al.: A successful defence of two physicians in this four week medical negligence trial relating to a laproscopic procedure and laparotomy where the plaintiff developed significant complications.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Barr et al. v. Rahimpour: A successful defence of a family physician in a clinical negligence claim relating to her prescription of an oral contraceptive to a 42 year-old woman who subsequently developed a pulmonary embolism. The action was dismissed against the physician one week into trial.</li>\r\n</ul>'),
